== Other ==
* It holds a dedication plaque in the autograph of the haiku poet [[:en:Masaoka Shiki|Masaoka Shiki]].
* It houses the [[:en:Yata no Kagami|Eight-Foot Mirror]] associated with the white snake legend.
* It possesses one of the largest taiko drums in the Kansai region, and the largest in Ehime Prefecture (Enju Taiko). This drum was crafted from the root portion of one of two sacred trees from the former Onsen District, Haishi Village, with the other located at [[:en:Ōyamazumi Shrine|Ōyamazumi Shrine]] (Ōmishima-cho, Imabari City).
* For a period, {{ill|Gokoku Shrines|lt=Gokoku Shrines|lt=Shokonsha|ja|招魂社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shokonsha|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}} (later known as {{ill|Ehime Prefectural Gokoku Shrine|ja|愛媛縣護國神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ehime Prefectural Gokoku Shrine|qq=|1=Ehime Gokoku Shrine|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11493796}}) was enshrined here.

== Access ==
* A 2‑minute walk from {{ill|Iyo Tetsu Bus|ja|伊予鉄バス|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Iyo Tetsu Bus|qq=|1=Iyotetsu Bus|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q53308357}} Shinritsu Bus Stop

